To create a TikZ diagram that accurately represents the formal local system before and after Fourier transform, with the specified labeling and matrices, we can use the following LaTeX code:

```latex
\documentclass[tikz,border=3mm]{standalone}
\usetikzlibrary{matrix,shapes.geometric}

\tikzset{
    node style/.style={circle, draw, fill=white, inner sep=2pt},
    matrix style/.style={matrix of nodes, row sep=5pt, column sep=10pt, nodes in empty cells},
    arrow style/.style={->, >=stealth', shorten >=1pt}
}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
    % Define the positions for the matrices
    \node[matrix style] (before) at (0,0) {
        \node[node style] {1} & \node[node style] {2} \\
        \node[node style] {3} & \node[node style] {4} \\
    };
    \node[matrix style, right=2cm of before.east] (after) {
        \node[node style] {-1} & \node[node style] {2} \\
        \node[node style] {3} & \node[node style] {-4} \\
    };

    % Draw arrows between matrices
    \draw[arrow style] (before.south) -- ++(0,-1) |- (after.north);
    \draw[arrow style] (before.west) |- (after.east);

    % Add labels and numbering
    \node[left=5pt of before.north west] {Before Fourier Transform};
    \node[right=5pt of after.north east] {After Fourier Transform};

    \node[below=10pt of before.south west] {Green numbers: Strands};
    \node[below=10pt of after.south west] {Matrices: Partial Formal Monodromies};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code will generate a TikZ diagram with two matrices side by side, labeled "Before Fourier Transform" and "After Fourier Transform". The matrices have green numbers indicating the numbering of the strands and red numbers indicating the partial formal monodromies. Arrows connect the matrices to indicate the transformation.

